<paragraph pageId="468" pageNumber="469">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="468" pageNumber="469">CAN</emphasis>
: AB, MB, NB, NT, ON, QC, SK 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="468" pageNumber="469">USA</emphasis>
: CT, ME, MN, NH, OH, PA, VT
</paragraph>
<caption httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/30926" pageId="468" pageNumber="469" start="Figure 25" startId="F25">
<paragraph pageId="468" pageNumber="469">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="468" pageNumber="469">Figure 25.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Darlington" authorityYear="1938" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Platypatrobus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="468" pageNumber="469" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lacustris">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="468" pageNumber="469">Platypatrobus lacustris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Darlington. Described in 1938, this species remained a great rarity for more than 20 years. The few specimens known had all been captured at light. Henri Goulet, then a summer student working at the Biosystematics Research Centre in Ottawa (now part of the Eastern Cereal and Oilseed Research Centre), found out that a mite of the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Evans" authorityYear="1957" class="Arachnida" family="Protodinychidae" genus="Protodinychus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="468" pageNumber="469" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="468" pageNumber="469">Protodinychus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, members of which occurred commonly in beaver houses, had been found on one of the specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Motschulsky" authorityYear="1844" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Patrobus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="468" pageNumber="469" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lacustris">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="468" pageNumber="469">Patrobus lacustris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Armed with this information, Goulet visited an abandoned beaver house in Gatineau Park in southwestern Quebec and found more than 50 specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Darlington" authorityYear="1938" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Platypatrobus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="468" pageNumber="469" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="468" pageNumber="469">Platypatrobus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The habitat requirements of the species were discovered: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Darlington" authorityYear="1938" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Platypatrobus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="468" pageNumber="469" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lacustris">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="468" pageNumber="469">Platypatrobus lacustris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
lives in the walls of active or recently deserted beaver houses.
</paragraph>
